# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alice-crary
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alice-crary/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:alice-crary/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:alice-crary/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:alice-crary/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:alice-crary/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:alice-crary/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Ayer was educated at Eton College and the University of Oxford, after which he studied the philosophy of logical positivism at the University of Vienna.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] From 1933 to 1940 he lectured on philosophy at Christ Church, Oxford.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] During the Second World War Ayer was a Special Operations Executive and MI6 agent.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Ayer was Grote Professor of the Philosophy of Mind and Logic at University College London from 1946 until 1959, after which he returned to Oxford to become Wykeham Professor of Logic at New College.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] He was president of the Aristotelian Society from 1951 to 1952 and knighted in 1970.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] He was known for his advocacy of humanism, and was the second president of the British Humanist Association (now known as Humanists UK).
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Ayer was born in St John's Wood, in north west London, to Jules Louis Cyprien Ayer and Reine (née Citroen), wealthy parents from continental Europe.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] His mother was from the Dutch-Jewish family that founded the Citroën car company in France; his father was a Swiss Calvinist financier who worked for the Rothschild family, including for their bank and as secretary to Alfred Rothschild.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Ayer was educated at Ascham St Vincent's School, a former boarding preparatory school for boys in the seaside town of Eastbourne in Sussex, where he started boarding at the relatively early age of seven for reasons to do with the First World War, and at Eton College, where he was a King's Scholar.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] At Eton, Ayer first became known for his characteristic bravado and precocity.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Though primarily interested in his intellectual pursuits, he was very keen on sports, particularly rugby, and reputedly played the Eton Wall Game very well.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] In the final examinations at Eton, Ayer came second in his year, and first in classics.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] In his final year, as a member of Eton's senior council, he unsuccessfully campaigned for the abolition of corporal punishment at the school.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] He won a classics scholarship to Christ Church, Oxford.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] He graduated with a BA with first-class honours.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] After graduating from Oxford, Ayer spent a year in Vienna, returned to England and published his first book, *Language, Truth and Logic*, in 1936.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] This first exposition in English of logical positivism as newly developed by the Vienna Circle, made Ayer at age 26 the *enfant terrible* of British philosophy.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] As a newly famous intellectual, he played a prominent role in the Oxford by-election campaign of 1938.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Ayer campaigned first for the Labour candidate Patrick Gordon Walker, and then for the joint Labour-Liberal "Independent Progressive" candidate Sandie Lindsay, who ran on an anti-appeasement platform against the Conservative candidate, Quintin Hogg, who ran as the appeasement candidate.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] The by-election, held on 27 October 1938, was quite close, with Hogg winning narrowly.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] In the Second World War, Ayer served as an officer in the Welsh Guards, chiefly in intelligence (Special Operations Executive (SOE) and MI6).
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] He was commissioned as a second lieutenant into the Welsh Guards from the Officer Cadet Training Unit on 21 September 1940.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] After the war, Ayer briefly returned to the University of Oxford where he became a fellow and Dean of Wadham College.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] He then taught philosophy at University College London from 1946 until 1959, during which time he started to appear on radio and television.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] He was an extrovert and social mixer who liked dancing and attending clubs in London and New York.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] He was also obsessed with sport: he had played rugby for Eton, and was a noted cricketer and a keen supporter of Tottenham Hotspur football team, where he was for many years a season ticket holder.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] For an academic, Ayer was an unusually well-connected figure in his time, with close links to 'high society' and the establishment.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Presiding over Oxford high-tables, he is often described as charming, but could also be intimidating.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Ayer was married four times to three women.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] His first marriage was from 1932 to 1941, to (Grace Isabel) Renée, with whom he had a son – allegedly the son of Ayer's friend and colleague Stuart Hampshire – and a daughter.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] In 1960, Ayer married Alberta Constance (Dee) Wells, with whom he had one son.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] That marriage was dissolved in 1983, and the same year, Ayer married Vanessa Salmon, the former wife of politician Nigel Lawson.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] She died in 1985, and in 1989 Ayer remarried Wells, who survived him.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] He also had a daughter with Hollywood columnist Sheilah Graham Westbrook.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] In 1950, Ayer attended the founding meeting of the Congress for Cultural Freedom in West Berlin, though he later said he went only because of the offer of a "free trip".
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] He gave a speech on why John Stuart Mill's conceptions of liberty and freedom were still valid in the 20th century.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Together with the historian Hugh Trevor-Roper, Ayer fought against Arthur Koestler and Franz Borkenau, arguing that they were far too dogmatic and extreme in their anti-communism, in fact proposing illiberal measures in the defence of liberty.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Adding to the tension was the location of the congress in West Berlin, together with the fact that the Korean War began on 25 June 1950, the fourth day of the congress, giving a feeling that the world was on the brink of war.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] From 1959 to his retirement in 1978, Ayer held the Wykeham Chair, Professor of Logic at Oxford.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] After his retirement, Ayer taught or lectured several times in the United States, including as a visiting professor at Bard College in 1987.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] At a party that same year held by fashion designer Fernando Sanchez, Ayer confronted Mike Tyson, who was forcing himself upon the then little-known model Naomi Campbell.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] When Ayer demanded that Tyson stop, Tyson reportedly asked, "Do you know who the fuck I am?
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] I'm the heavyweight champion of the world", to which Ayer replied, "And I am the former Wykeham Professor of Logic.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] I suggest that we talk about this like rational men".
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Ayer and Tyson then began to talk, allowing Campbell to slip out.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Gully Wells, Ayer's stepdaughter via Dee Wells, records the same event with some slight variation of detail.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Ayer was also involved in politics, including anti-Vietnam War activism, supporting the Labour Party (and later the Social Democratic Party), chairing the Campaign Against Racial Discrimination in Sport, and serving as president of the Homosexual Law Reform Society.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] In 1978 he was interviewed for Bryan Magee's *Men of Ideas* television show, where he spoke about logical positivism and its legacy, later in 1987 he appeared on Magee's *The Great Philosophers* in an episode centering on Frege, Russell and Modern Logic.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] In 1988, a year before his death, Ayer wrote an article titled "What I saw when I was dead", describing an unusual near-death experience after his heart stopped for four minutes as he choked on smoked salmon.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] From 1980 to 1989 he lived at 51 York Street, Marylebone, where a memorial plaque was unveiled on 19 November 1995.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] In *Language, Truth and Logic* (1936), Ayer presents the verification principle as the only valid basis for philosophy.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Unless logical or empirical verification is possible, statements like "God exists" or "charity is good" are not true or untrue but meaningless, and may thus be excluded or ignored.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Religious language in particular is unverifiable and as such literally nonsense.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Mace's opinion that metaphysics is a form of intellectual poetry.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] The stance that a belief in God denotes no verifiable hypothesis is sometimes referred to as igtheism (for example, by Paul Kurtz).
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] In later years, Ayer reiterated that he did not believe in God and began to call himself an atheist.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] He followed in the footsteps of Bertrand Russell by debating religion with the Jesuit scholar Frederick Copleston.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] He focuses on propositions of the first class – moral judgements – saying that those of the second class belong to science, those of the third are mere commands, and those of the fourth (which are considered normative ethics as opposed to meta-ethics) are too concrete for ethical philosophy.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Ayer argues that moral judgements cannot be translated into non-ethical, empirical terms and thus cannot be verified; in this he agrees with ethical intuitionists.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] But he differs from intuitionists by discarding appeals to intuition of non-empirical moral truths as "worthless" since the intuition of one person often contradicts that of another.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Between 1945 and 1947, together with Russell and George Orwell, Ayer contributed a series of articles to *Polemic*, a short-lived British *Magazine of Philosophy, Psychology, and Aesthetics* edited by the ex-Communist Humphrey Slater.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Ayer was closely associated with the British humanist movement.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] He was an Honorary Associate of the Rationalist Press Association from 1947 until his death.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] He was elected a Foreign Honorary Member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1963.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] In 1965, he became the first president of the Agnostics' Adoption Society and in the same year succeeded Julian Huxley as president of the British Humanist Association, a post he held until 1970.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] In 1968 he edited *The Humanist Outlook*, a collection of essays on the meaning of humanism.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] He was one of the signers of the Humanist Manifesto.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Ayer is best known for popularising the verification principle, in particular through his presentation of it in *Language, Truth, and Logic*.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] The principle was at the time at the heart of the debates of the so-called Vienna Circle, which Ayer had visited as a young guest.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Others, including the circle's leading light, Moritz Schlick, were already writing papers on the issue.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Ayer's formulation was that a sentence can be meaningful only if it has verifiable empirical import; otherwise, it is either "analytical" if tautologous or "metaphysical" (i.e. meaningless, or "literally senseless").
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] He started to work on the book at the age of 23 and it was published when he was 26.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Ayer's philosophical ideas were deeply influenced by those of the Vienna Circle and David Hume.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] His clear, vibrant and polemical exposition of them makes *Language, Truth and Logic* essential reading on the tenets of logical empiricism; the book is regarded as a classic of 20th-century analytic philosophy and is widely read in philosophy courses around the world.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Ayer wrote two books on the philosopher Bertrand Russell, *Russell and Moore: The Analytic Heritage* (1971) and *Russell* (1972).
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] He also wrote an introductory book on the philosophy of David Hume and a short biography of Voltaire.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Ayer was a strong critic of the German philosopher Martin Heidegger.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] As a logical positivist, Ayer was in conflict with Heidegger's vast, overarching theories of existence.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Ayer considered them completely unverifiable through empirical demonstration and logical analysis, and this sort of philosophy an unfortunate strain in modern thought.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] He considered Heidegger the worst example of such philosophy, which Ayer believed entirely useless.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] In *Philosophy in the Twentieth Century*, Ayer accuses Heidegger of "surprising ignorance" or "unscrupulous distortion" and "what can fairly be described as charlatanism".
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] In 1972–73, Ayer gave the Gifford Lectures at the University of St Andrews, later published as *The Central Questions of Philosophy*.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] He still believed in the viewpoint he shared with the logical positivists: that large parts of what was traditionally called philosophy—including metaphysics, theology and aesthetics—were not matters that could be judged true or false, and that it was thus meaningless to discuss them.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] In *The Concept of a Person and Other Essays* (1963), Ayer heavily criticised Wittgenstein's private language argument.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Ayer's sense-data theory in *Foundations of Empirical Knowledge* was famously criticised by fellow Oxonian J.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Austin in *Sense and Sensibilia*, a landmark 1950s work of ordinary language philosophy.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Ayer responded in the essay "Has Austin Refuted the Sense-datum Theory?", which can be found in his *Metaphysics and Common Sense* (1969).
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Ayer was awarded a knighthood as Knight Bachelor in the London Gazette on 1 January 1970.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] Ayer's biographer, Ben Rogers, deposited 7 boxes of research material accumulated through the writing process at University College London in 2007.
[src:alice-crary/a-j-ayer] The material was donated in collaboration with Ayer's family.
[src:alice-crary/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:alice-crary/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:alice-crary/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:alice-crary/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:alice-crary/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:alice-crary/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:alice-crary/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:alice-crary/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:alice-crary/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:alice-crary/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:alice-crary/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:alice-crary/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:alice-crary/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:alice-crary/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:alice-crary/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:alice-crary/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:alice-crary/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:alice-crary/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:alice-crary/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:alice-crary/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:alice-crary/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:alice-crary/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:alice-crary/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:alice-crary/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:alice-crary/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:alice-crary/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:alice-crary/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:alice-crary/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:alice-crary/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:alice-crary/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:alice-crary/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:alice-crary/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:alice-crary/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:alice-crary/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:alice-crary/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:alice-crary/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:alice-crary/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:alice-crary/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:alice-crary/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:alice-crary/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:alice-crary/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:alice-crary/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:alice-crary/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:alice-crary/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:alice-crary/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:alice-crary/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:alice-crary/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:alice-crary/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:alice-crary/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:alice-crary/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:alice-crary/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:alice-crary/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:alice-crary/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:alice-crary/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:alice-crary/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:alice-crary/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:alice-crary/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] The resultant theory was challenged and refined several times in the decades following its original publication in 1971.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] A significant reappraisal was published in the 1985 essay "Justice as Fairness" and the 2001 book *Justice as Fairness: A Restatement* in which Rawls further developed his two central principles for his discussion of justice.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Together, they assert that society should be structured to provide the greatest possible degree of liberty to its members, limited only by the principle that one individual's liberty must not infringe upon the liberty of others.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Secondly, inequalities – either social or economic – are only to be allowed if the worst off will be better off than they might be under an equal distribution.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Finally, if an inequality is to be justified on the grounds of its benefits, it must not create additional barriers for those without resources to access positions of power, such as public office.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] In *A Theory of Justice,* Rawls argues for a principled reconciliation of liberty and equality that is meant to apply to the basic structure of a well-ordered society.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Central to this effort is an account of the circumstances of justice, inspired by David Hume, and a fair choice situation for parties facing such circumstances, similar to some of Immanuel Kant's views.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Principles of justice are sought to guide the conduct of the parties.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] These parties are recognized to face moderate scarcity, and they are neither naturally altruistic nor purely egoistic.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] They have ends which they seek to advance but prefer to advance them through cooperation with others on mutually acceptable terms.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls offers a model of a fair choice situation (the original position with its veil of ignorance) within which parties would hypothetically choose mutually acceptable principles of justice.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Under such constraints, Rawls believes that parties would find his favoured principles of justice to be especially attractive, winning out over varied alternatives, including utilitarian and right-wing libertarian accounts.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls belongs to the social contract tradition, although he takes a different view from that of previous thinkers.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Specifically, Rawls develops what he claims are principles of justice through the use of an artificial device or thought experiment he calls the *Original position*; in which, everyone decides principles of justice from behind a veil of ignorance.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] [N]o one knows his place in society, his class position or social status, nor does anyone know his fortune in the distribution of natural assets and abilities, his intelligence, strength, and the like.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] I shall even assume that the parties do not know their conceptions of the good or their special psychological propensities.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] The principles of justice are chosen behind a veil of ignorance.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] They are the principles that rational and free persons concerned to further their own interests would accept in an initial position of equality as defining the fundamentals of the terms of their association.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] If an individual does not know how he will end up in his own conceived society, he is likely not going to privilege any one class of people, but rather develop a scheme of justice that treats all fairly.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] In particular, Rawls claims that those in the *Original Position* would adopt two principles, the second of which is a maximin strategy which would maximize the prospects of the least well-off.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls bases his *Original Position* on a "thin theory of the good" which he says "explains the rationality underlying choice of principles in the Original Position".
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] A full theory of the good follows after we derive principles from the original position.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls claims that the parties in the original position would adopt two such principles, which would then govern the assignment of rights and duties and regulate the distribution of social and economic advantages across society.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] The difference principle permits inequalities in the distribution of goods only if those inequalities benefit the worst-off members of society.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls believes that this principle would be a rational choice for the representatives in the original position for the following reason: Each member of society has an equal claim on their society's goods.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Natural attributes should not affect this claim, so the basic right of any individual, before further considerations are taken into account, must be to an equal share in material wealth.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] What, then, could justify unequal distribution?
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls argues that inequality is acceptable only if it is to the advantage of those who are worst-off.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] The agreement that stems from the original position is both *hypothetical* and *ahistorical*.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] It is hypothetical in the sense that the principles to be derived are what the parties would, under certain legitimating conditions, agree to, not what they have agreed to.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls seeks to use an argument that the principles of justice are what *would* be agreed upon if people were in the hypothetical situation of the original position and that those principles have moral weight as a result of that.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] It is ahistorical in the sense that it is not supposed that the agreement has ever been, or indeed could ever have been, derived in the real world outside of carefully limited experimental exercises.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls modifies and develops the principles of justice throughout his book.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] The first principle is often called the *greatest equal liberty principle*.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls orders the principles of justice lexically, as follows: **1**, **2b**, **2a**.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] The *greatest equal liberty principle* takes priority, followed by the *equal opportunity principle* and finally the *difference principle*.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] The first principle must be satisfied before 2b, and 2b must be satisfied before 2a.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] The *greatest equal liberty principle* is mainly concerned with the distribution of rights and liberties.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] His position is at least in some sense egalitarian, with a provision that inequalities are allowed when they benefit the least advantaged.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] An important consequence of Rawls' view is that inequalities can actually be just, as long as they are to the benefit of the least well off.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] His argument for this position rests heavily on the claim that morally arbitrary factors (for example, the family one is born into) should not determine one's life chances or opportunities.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Further, the just savings principle requires that some sort of material respect is left for future generations.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Although Rawls is ambiguous about what this means, it can generally be understood as "a contribution to those coming later".
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] The stipulation in 2b is lexically prior to that in 2a.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] In 1972, *A Theory of Justice* was reviewed in *The New York Times Book Review* by Marshall Cohen, who described the work as "magisterial," and suggested that Rawls' use of the techniques of analytic philosophy made the book the "most formidable" defense of the social contract tradition to date.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Michael Sandel criticized Rawls in *Liberalism and the Limits of Justice* (1982), arguing that Rawls encourages people to think about justice while divorced from the values and aspirations that define who they are as persons and that allow people to determine what justice is.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Susan Moller Okin wrote in *Justice, Gender, and the Family* (1989) that Rawls had provided "the most influential of all twentieth-century theories of justice", but criticized him for failing to account for the injustices and hierarchies embedded in familial relations.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] In his book *Black Rights / White Wrongs*, philosopher Charles W.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Mills critiques the underlying assumptions of Rawls’s work as inherently white, and thus subject to glaring blind spots.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] The economist Amartya Sen has raised concerns over Rawls' emphasis on primary social goods, arguing in *Inequality Reexamined* (1992) that we should attend not only to the distribution of primary goods, but also how effectively people are able to use those goods to pursue their ends.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Norman Daniels has wondered why health care should not be treated as a primary good, and some of his subsequent work has addressed this question, arguing for a right to health care within a broadly Rawlsian framework.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Sen critiques and attempts to revitalize *A Theory of Justice* in *The Idea of Justice* (2009).
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] He credits Rawls for revitalizing the interest in the ideas of what justice means and the stress put on fairness, objectivity, equality of opportunity, removal of poverty, and freedom.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] However, Sen, as part of his general critique of the contractarian tradition, states that ideas about a perfectly just world do not help redress actual existing inequality.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Sen faults Rawls for overemphasizing institutions as guarantors of justice and not considering the effects of human behaviour on the institutions' ability to maintain a just society.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Sen believes Rawls understates the difficulty in getting everyone in society to adhere to the norms of a just society.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] He also claims that Rawls' position that there be only one possible outcome of the reflective equilibrium behind the veil of ignorance is misguided.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] In contrast to Rawls, Sen believes that multiple conflicting, yet just, principles may arise and that this undermines the multistep processes that Rawls laid out as leading to a perfectly just society.
[src:alice-crary/a-theory-of-justice] Through this, Cohen argues that Rawls's theory is not a theory of justice.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p01] The *Treatise* is a classic statement of philosophical empiricism, scepticism, and naturalism.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p01] In the introduction Hume presents the idea of placing all science and philosophy on a novel foundation: namely, an empirical investigation into human nature.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p01] Impressed by Isaac Newton's achievements in the physical sciences, Hume sought to introduce the same experimental method of reasoning into the study of human psychology, with the aim of discovering the "extent and force of human understanding".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p01] Against the philosophical rationalists, Hume argues that the passions, rather than reason, cause human behaviour.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p01] He introduces the famous problem of induction, arguing that inductive reasoning and our beliefs regarding cause and effect cannot be justified by reason; instead, our faith in induction and causation is caused by mental habit and custom.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p01] Isaiah Berlin wrote of Hume that "no man has influenced the history of philosophy to a deeper or more disturbing degree".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p01] Jerry Fodor wrote of Hume's *Treatise* that it is "the foundational document of cognitive science".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p01] However, the public in Britain at the time did not agree, nor in the end did Hume himself agree, reworking the material in both *An Enquiry Concerning Human Understanding* (1748) and *An Enquiry Concerning the Principles of Morals* (1751).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p01] Regarding *An Enquiry Concerning the Principles of Morals*, Hume said it is "of all my writings, historical, philosophical, or literary, incomparably the best".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume's introduction presents the idea of placing all science and philosophy on a novel foundation: namely, an empirical investigation into human psychology.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But since the truth "must lie very deep and abstruse" where "the greatest geniuses" have not found it, careful reasoning is still needed.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] According to Hume, knowledge of "the extent and force of human understanding,... the nature of the ideas we employ, and... the operations we perform in our reasonings" is needed to make real intellectual progress.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] So he hopes "to explain the principles of human nature", thereby "propos[ing] a compleat system of the sciences, built on a foundation almost entirely new, and the only one upon which they can stand with any security".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But an *a priori* psychology would be hopeless: the science of man must be pursued by the experimental methods of the natural sciences.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] This means we must rest content with well-confirmed empirical generalisations, forever ignorant of "the ultimate original qualities of human nature".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And in the absence of controlled experiments, we are left to "glean up our experiments in this science from a cautious observation of human life, and take them as they appear in the common course of the world, by men's behaviour in company, in affairs, and in their pleasures".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume begins by arguing that each simple idea is derived from a simple impression so that all our ideas are ultimately derived from experience: thus Hume accepts concept empiricism and rejects the purely intellectual and innate ideas found in rationalist philosophy.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Our complex ideas, he acknowledges, may not directly correspond to anything in experience (e.g., we can form the complex idea of a heavenly city).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But each *simple* idea (e.g., of the colour red) directly corresponds to a simple impression resembling it—and this regular correspondence suggests that the two are causally connected.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Since the simple impressions come before the simple ideas, and since those without functioning senses (e.g., blindness) end up lacking the corresponding ideas, Hume concludes that simple ideas must be derived from simple impressions.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Notoriously, Hume considers and dismisses the 'missing shade of blue' counterexample.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Briefly examining impressions, Hume then distinguishes between impressions of sensation (found in sense experience) and impressions of reflection (found mainly in emotional experience), only to set aside any further discussion for Book 2's treatment of the passions.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But despite this freedom, the imagination still tends to follow general psychological principles as it moves from one idea to another: this is the "association of ideas".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Here Hume finds three "natural relations" guiding the imagination: resemblance, contiguity, and causation.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But the imagination remains free to compare ideas along any of seven "philosophical relations": resemblance, identity, space/time, quantity/number, quality/degree, contrariety, and causation.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume finishes Part 1 by arguing (following Berkeley) that so-called "abstract ideas" are in fact only particular ideas used in a general way.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Thus the general term "triangle" both calls up an idea of some particular triangle and activates the custom disposing the imagination to call up any other ideas of particular triangles.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Finally, Hume uses this account to explain so-called "distinctions of reason" (e.g., distinguishing the motion of a body from the body itself).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Though such distinctions are strictly impossible, Hume argues, we achieve the same effect by noting the various points of resemblance between different objects.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume's "system concerning space and time" features two main doctrines: the *finitist* doctrine that space and time are not infinitely divisible, and the *relationist* doctrine that space and time cannot be conceived apart from objects.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume begins by arguing that, since "the capacity of the mind is limited", our imagination and senses must eventually reach a minimum: ideas and impressions so minute as to be indivisible.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And since nothing can be more minute, our indivisible ideas are "adequate representations of the most minute parts of [spatial] extension".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Upon consideration of these "clear ideas", Hume presents a few arguments to demonstrate that space and time are not infinitely divisible, but are instead composed of indivisible points.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] On his account, the idea of space is abstracted from our sense experience (arrangements of coloured or tangible points), and the idea of time from the changing succession of our own perceptions.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And this means that space and time cannot be conceived on their own, apart from objects arranged in space or changing across time.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Thus we have no idea of absolute space and time, so that vacuums and time without change are ruled out.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume then defends his two doctrines against objections.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] In defending his finitism against mathematical objections, he argues that the *definitions* of geometry support his account.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Next, Hume defends his relationist doctrine, critically examining the alleged idea of a vacuum.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] In the final section, Hume accounts for our ideas of existence and of external existence.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] First, he argues that there is no distinct impression from which to derive the idea of existence.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Instead, this idea is nothing more than the idea of any object, so that thinking of something and thinking of it as existent is the very same thing.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Next, he argues that we cannot conceive of anything beyond our own perceptions; thus our conception of the existence of external objects is at most a "relative idea".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume recalls the seven philosophical relations, and divides them into two classes: four which can give us "knowledge and certainty", and three which cannot.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] (This division reappears in Hume's first *Enquiry* as "relations of ideas" and "matters of fact", respectively.) As for the four relations, he notes, all can yield knowledge by way of *intuition*: immediate recognition of a relation (e.g., one idea as brighter in colour than another).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But with one of the four, "proportions in quantity or number", we commonly achieve knowledge by way of *demonstration*: step-by-step inferential reasoning (e.g., proofs in geometry).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume makes two remarks on demonstrative reasoning in mathematics: that geometry is not as precise as algebra (though still generally reliable), and that mathematical ideas are not "spiritual and refin'd perceptions", but instead copied from impressions.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] As for the other three relations, two of them (identity and space/time) are simply a matter of immediate sensory *perception* (e.g., one object next to another).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But with the last relation, causation, we can go beyond the senses, by way of a form of inferential reasoning he calls *probable reasoning*.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Here Hume embarks on his celebrated examination of causation, beginning with the question *From what impression do we derive our idea of causation?* All that can be observed in a single instance of cause and effect are two relations: contiguity in space, and priority in time.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But Hume insists that our idea of causation also includes a mysterious *necessary connection* linking cause to effect.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] He concludes that our acceptance of this maxim must be somehow drawn "from observation and experience", and thus turns to the second question.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume develops a detailed three-stage psychological account of how probable reasoning works (i.e., how "the judgement" operates).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] First, our senses or memory must present us with some object: our confidence in this perception (our "assent") is simply a matter of its force and vivacity.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Second, we must make an inference, moving from our perception of this object to an idea of another object: since the two objects are perfectly distinct from each other, this inference must draw on past experience of the two objects being observed together again and again.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] (This "constant conjunction" is promptly filed alongside contiguity and priority, in Hume's still-developing account of our idea of causation.) But what exactly is the process by which we draw on past experience and make an inference from the present object to the other object?
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Here the famous "problem of induction" arises.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume argues that this all-important inference cannot be accounted for by any process of reasoning: neither demonstrative reasoning nor probable reasoning.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Not demonstrative reasoning: it cannot be demonstrated that the future will resemble the past, for "[w]e can at least conceive a change in the course of nature", in which the future significantly differs from the past.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And not probable reasoning: that kind of reasoning itself draws on past experience, which means it *presupposes* that the future will resemble the past.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] In other words, in explaining how we draw on past experience to make causal inferences, we cannot appeal to a kind of reasoning that itself draws on past experience—that would be a vicious circle that gets us nowhere.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] The inference is not based on reasoning, Hume concludes, but on the *association of ideas*: our innate psychological tendency to move along the three "natural relations".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Recall that one of the three is causation: thus when two objects are constantly conjoined in our experience, observing the one naturally leads us to form an idea of the other.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] This brings us to the third and final stage of Hume's account, our *belief* in the other object as we conclude the process of probable reasoning (e.g., seeing wolf tracks and concluding confidently that they were caused by wolves).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] On his account of belief, the only difference between a *believed* idea and a merely *conceived* idea lies in the belief's additional force and vivacity.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And there is a general psychological tendency for any lively perception to transfer some of its force and vivacity to any other perception naturally related to it (e.g., seeing "the picture of an absent friend" makes our idea of the friend more lively, by the natural relation of resemblance).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Thus in probable reasoning, on Hume's account, our lively perception of the one object not only leads us to form a mere idea of the other object, but *enlivens* that idea into a full-fledged belief.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume now pauses for a more general examination of the psychology of belief.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Similarly, other kinds of custom-based conditioning (e.g., rote learning, repeated lying) can induce strong beliefs.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Next, Hume considers the mutual influence of reasoning and the passions, and of belief and the imagination.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Only beliefs can have motivational influence: it is the additional force and vivacity of a belief (as opposed to a mere idea) that makes it "able to operate on the will and passions".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And in turn we tend to favor beliefs that flatter our passions.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Likewise, a story must be somewhat realistic or familiar to please the imagination, and an overactive imagination can result in delusional belief.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume sees these diverse phenomena as confirming his "force and vivacity" account of belief.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Indeed, we keep ourselves "from augmenting our belief upon every increase of the force and vivacity of our ideas" only by soberly reflecting on past experience and forming "general rules" for ourselves.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume then examines probable reasoning under conditions of empirical uncertainty, distinguishing "proofs" (conclusive empirical evidence) from mere "probabilities" (less than conclusive empirical evidence).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume's discussion of probability finishes with a section on common cognitive biases, starting with recency effects.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] First, the more recent the event whose cause or effect we are looking for, the stronger our belief in the conclusion.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Second, the more recent the observations we draw on, the stronger our belief in the conclusion.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Third, the longer and more discontinuous a line of reasoning, the weaker our belief in the conclusion.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Fourth, irrational prejudices can be formed by overgeneralizing from experience: the imagination is unduly influenced by any "superfluous circumstances" that have frequently been observed to accompany the circumstances that actually matter.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And paradoxically, the only way to correct for the pernicious influence of "general rules" is to follow other general rules, formed by reflecting on the circumstances of the case and our cognitive limitations.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Throughout the section, Hume uses his "force and vivacity" account of belief to account for these "unphilosophical" influences on our reasoning.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Having completed his account of probable reasoning, Hume returns to the mysterious idea of necessary connection.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] He rejects some proposed sources of this idea: not from the "known qualities of matter", nor from God, nor from some "unknown quality" of matter, nor from our power to move our body at will.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] For all ideas derive from experience, and in no single case do we observe anything like a necessary connection linking cause to effect.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But the idea *does* arise upon repeated observations, and since mere repetition cannot produce anything new in the objects themselves, the idea must therefore derive from something new in our mind.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Thus he concludes that the idea of necessary connection is derived from inside: from the feeling we experience when the mind (conditioned by repeated observation) makes a causal inference.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And though his conclusion is shocking to common sense, Hume explains it away by noting that "the mind has a great propensity to spread itself on external objects".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Finally, he offers two definitions of "cause": one in terms of the *objects* (viz. their relations of priority, contiguity, and constant conjunction), and another in terms of the *mind* (viz. the causal inference it makes upon observing the objects).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume finishes Part 3 with two brief sections.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] First, he presents eight rules for empirically identifying true causes: after all, if we leave aside experience, "[a]ny thing may produce any thing".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Second, he compares human reason with animal reason, a comparison which clinches the case for his associationist account of probable reasoning: after all, animals are clearly capable of learning from experience through conditioning, and yet they are clearly incapable of any sophisticated reasoning.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume begins Part 4 by arguing that "all knowledge degenerates into probability", due to the possibility of error: even the rock solid certainty of mathematics becomes less than certain when we remember that we might have made a mistake somewhere.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But things get worse: reflection on the fallibility of our mind, and meta-reflection on the fallibility of this first reflection, and so on *ad infinitum*, ultimately reduces probability into total scepticism—or at least it *would*, if our beliefs were governed by the understanding alone.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But according to Hume, this "extinction of belief" does not actually happen: having beliefs is part of human nature, which only confirms Hume's account of belief as "more properly an act of the sensitive, than of the cogitative part of our natures".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And as for *why* we do not sink into total scepticism, Hume argues that the mind has a limited quantity of "force and activity", and that difficult and abstruse reasoning "strain[s] the imagination", "hinder[ing] the regular flowing of the passions and sentiments".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] As a result, extremely subtle sceptical argumentation is unable to overpower and destroy our beliefs.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Next comes an extremely lengthy account of why we believe in an external physical world: i.e., why we think objects have a *continued* (existing when unobserved) and *distinct* (existing external to and independent of the mind) existence.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume considers three potential sources of this belief—the senses, reason, and the imagination.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] It's not the senses: clearly they are incapable of informing us of anything existing unobserved.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And it's not reason: even children and fools believe in an external world, and nearly all of us naïvely take our perceptions to be objects with a continued and distinct existence, which goes *against* reason.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] So this belief must come from the imagination.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But only some of our impressions bring about the belief: namely, impressions with *constancy* (invariableness in appearance over time) and *coherence* (regularity in changing appearances).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Thus Hume proceeds to develop an account of how the imagination, fed with coherent and constant impressions, brings about belief in objects with continued (and therefore distinct) existence.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Given *coherent* impressions, we have only one way of accounting for our observations consistently with past experience: we form the supposition that certain objects exist unperceived.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And since this supposes more regularity than is found in past observation, causal reasoning alone cannot explain it: thus Hume invokes the imagination's tendency to continue in any "train of thinking" inertially, "like a galley put in motion by the oars".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But to explain "so vast an edifice, as... the continu'd existence of all external bodies", Hume finds it necessary to bring *constancy* into his account, as follows: (1) Identity is characterised as invariableness and uninterruptedness over time.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] (2) Since the mind tends to confuse closely resembling ideas, it will naturally confuse a case of interrupted observation of an invariable object with a case of perfect identity.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] (3) This combination of perfect identity and interrupted observation creates cognitive dissonance, which is resolved by fabricating continued existence.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] (4) This fiction is enlivened into a full-fledged belief by the memory's "lively impressions" of the observed object.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But this naïve belief in the continued and distinct existence of our perceptions is *false*, as is easily shown by simple observations.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Philosophers therefore distinguish mental perceptions from external objects.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But, Hume argues, this philosophical "system of a double existence" could never arise directly from reason or the imagination.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Instead, it is "the monstrous offspring of two principles", viz. our naïve belief in the continued and distinct existence of our perceptions, along with our more reflective conclusion that perceptions must depend upon the mind.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] It is only by passing through the naïve natural belief that the imagination fabricates this "arbitrarily invent[ed]" philosophical system.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume ends by voicing strong doubts about any system based on "such trivial qualities of the fancy", and recommending "[c]arelessness and in-attention" as the only remedy for scepticism.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Next, Hume presents a brief critique of "antient philosophy" (traditional Aristotelianism) and "modern philosophy" (post-Scientific Revolution mechanical philosophy), focusing on their rival conceptions of external objects.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] As for the incomprehensible "fictions of the antient philosophy", he thinks they can shed further light on human psychology.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] We begin with contradictions in "our ideas of bodies": between seeing bodies as ever-changing bundles of distinct qualities, and seeing bodies as simple unities that retain their identity across time.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] We reconcile these contradictions by fabricating "something unknown and invisible" that underlies change and unifies the distinct qualities together: i.e., the *substance* of traditional metaphysics.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Similar fictions, fabricated by the imagination to resolve similar difficulties, include *substantial forms*, *accidents*, and *occult qualities*, all meaningless jargon used only to hide our ignorance.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Modern philosophy, however, claims to disown the "trivial propensit[ies] of the imagination" and follow only solid reason (or, for Hume, "the solid, permanent, and consistent principles of the imagination").
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Its "fundamental principle" is that secondary qualities ("colours, sounds, tastes, smells, heat and cold") are "nothing but impressions in the mind", as opposed to the primary qualities ("motion, extension, and solidity") that exist in reality.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But Hume argues that primary qualities cannot be conceived apart from the secondary qualities.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Thus if we follow solid reason and exclude the latter, we will be forced to contradict our own senses by excluding the former as well, thereby denying the entire external world.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume then examines "the nature of the mind", starting with the materialist-dualist debate over the substance of the mind.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] He rejects the whole question as "unintelligible", for we have no impression (and therefore no idea) of any substance, and defining "substance" as "something which may exist by itself" does not help (each of our perceptions, Hume argues, would then count as a distinct substance).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Turning to the question of the "*local conjunction*" of mind and matter, he considers and endorses the anti-materialist argument which asks how unextended thoughts and feelings could possibly be conjoined at some location to an extended substance like a body.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But the contrary problem arises for dualists: how can extended perceptions (of extended objects) possibly be conjoined to a simple substance?
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Finally, Hume weighs in on the topic of personal identity.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Notoriously, he claims that introspective experience reveals nothing like a *self* (i.e., a mental substance with identity and simplicity), but only an ever-changing bundle of particular perceptions.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And so he gives a psychological account of why we believe in personal identity, arguing that "the identity, which we ascribe to the mind of man, is only a fictitious one, and of a like kind with that which we ascribe to vegetables and animal bodies".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And consequently, leaving aside the fictions we invent, questions of personal identity are far too hazy to be answered with precision.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume finishes Book 1 with a deeply sceptical interlude.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Before continuing his "accurate anatomy of human nature" in Books 2 and 3, he anxiously ruminates: the "danger" of trusting his feeble faculties, along with the "solitude" of leaving behind established opinion, make his "bold enterprises" look foolhardy.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And how much should we trust our imagination?
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Here a dilemma looms: if we follow the imagination wherever it leads, we end up with ridiculous absurdities; if we follow only its "general and more establish'd properties", we sink into total scepticism.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] As Hume writes: "[w]e have, therefore, no choice left but betwixt a false reason and none at all." Faced with this dilemma, we tend to just forget about it and move on, though Hume finds himself verging on an intellectual breakdown.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume begins by recalling Book 1's distinction between impressions of sensation ("original impressions", arising from physical causes outside the mind) and impressions of reflection ("secondary impressions", arising from other perceptions within the mind), examining only the latter.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Pride and humility are indirect passions, and Hume's account of the two is his leading presentation of the psychological mechanisms responsible for the indirect passions.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Since we cannot put the *feeling* of a passion into words, Hume identifies passions via their characteristic *causes and effects*.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] The *cause* of a passion is what calls up the passion: e.g., pride can be caused by one's beautiful house.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] A cause can be subdivided into the *subject* itself (e.g., one's house) and the *quality* of the subject that "operates on the passions" (e.g., the beauty of one's house).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] The *object* of a passion is what the passion is ultimately directed at: pride and humility are both directed at oneself.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume's account relies on three mechanisms.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] First, the "association of ideas": the mind tends to move from one idea to another idea that is naturally related to it.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Second, the "association of impressions": the mind tends to move from one passion to another passion that resembles it in feeling (e.g., from joy to love).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Third, their "mutual assistance": if we feel a passion towards something, we will tend to feel a resembling passion towards something else naturally related to it (e.g., from anger at one person to impatience at a related person).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Applying all this to pride, Hume argues that the pleasant sensation of pride, directed at ourselves, naturally tends to be called up when something naturally related to ourselves produces a pleasant sensation of its own.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Likewise with humility: when something naturally related to ourselves produces an unpleasant sensation of its own, it tends to make us ashamed of ourselves.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] These indirect passions are thus the product of the "double relation of impressions and ideas".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume completes his account with five "limitations".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] First, in order for pride or humility to be produced, the relation of ideas must be a relatively close one.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Second, because our judgements are strongly influenced by "comparison", this relation must apply only to ourselves or a few others.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Third, the cause of pride or humility must be something evident to ourselves and others.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Fourth, this cause must be a long-lasting one.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Fifth, general rules have a strong influence on our passions, leading us to overlook occasional anomalies.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] In the next three sections, Hume puts his account to the test by examining three causes of pride and humility: the qualities of one's mind, of one's body, and of external objects.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] First, the qualities of the mind: our virtues and vices.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Here Hume's main point is that, whatever the true nature of moral evaluation, whether it is a matter of innate moral psychology (Hume's own view), or instead self-interest and cultural training (the view of Hobbes and Mandeville), his account will hold up.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] For, on either theory, virtues produce a pleasant sensation of their own and vices a painful sensation of their own.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Next come the qualities of the body: physical beauty and deformity.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Here Hume's main point is that the beauty or deformity of something's structure is nothing more than its power to produce pleasure or pain in us.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Finally, Hume examines the qualities of external objects related to us.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Though the natural relation of *resemblance* has little influence, he explains, external objects do not cause pride or humility without some relation of *contiguity* or *causation*—a fact he takes to confirm his overall account.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] After a few minor illustrations, Hume explains why pride in one's ancestors is magnified when the family enjoys uninterrupted possession of land, and when it is passed down from male to male (both of the conditions, he claims, serve to strengthen the relation of ideas).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume devotes an entire section to "property and riches".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But it is more difficult to accommodate *riches*: i.e., the mere power of acquiring the comforts of life.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] For Hume's earlier account of causation eliminated the distinction between power and the exercise of power, as well as the very idea of an unexercised power—and how can I take pride in mere coins and paper without such an idea?
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume finishes by noting the pride we take in power over others, a pride enhanced by comparing our condition to theirs (thus humans are prouder to own other humans than to own sophisticated machinery).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume's next section adds a new kind of cause of pride and humility: viz., *reputation*, a "secondary cause" grounded in the enormously important mechanism of *sympathy*.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] For Hume, sympathy with others, or "communication", is that mechanism by which we naturally tend to receive and share in the passions and opinions of those we feel close to.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] We start by observing "external signs" (e.g., smiling or speaking) and forming an idea of another's sentiments.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Since our extremely vivid conception of ourselves will tend to enliven any related idea, the closer the relation we see between ourselves and the other person, the more vivid our idea of their sentiments.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And if this relation is close enough, we will end up actually feeling their passion or believing their opinion: i.e., our idea of their passion or opinion will grow so lively as to become the very passion or opinion itself.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] This mirrors Hume's earlier account of causal reasoning: both processes move along the three natural relations, channeling the force and vivacity of vivid perceptions into faint ideas, enlivening them into much stronger perceptions.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Pride or shame in one's reputation, Hume continues, stems primarily from the sympathetically communicated opinions of others.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] But additional factors play a role: others might be seen as a good judge of character ("authority"), and the very question of one's self-worth is both emotionally heightened and apt to evoke a self-conscious deference to the opinions of others.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] The resulting account explains various observations: why pride is affected more by the opinions of certain people (those whose character we like, whose judgement we respect, or who we have known for a long time), and less by opinions we know to be false (and thus cannot share in).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume finishes by illustrating and confirming his account with a concrete example (viz., a man from a high-class family fallen on hard times leaving home to do manual labour elsewhere), and considering some minor objections.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] In the final section, Hume seeks to confirm his overall account of pride and humility by applying it to animals.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] Hume's treatment of love and hatred is much like his treatment of pride and humility: all four are indirect passions produced by a double relation of impressions and ideas.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] As Part 2 begins, he again distinguishes object from cause, and quality from subject; whereas pride and humility were directed at oneself, love and hatred is directed at "some other person".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] As before, a relation of ideas is needed between the cause of love or hatred and the person loved or hated, and a relation of impressions between the cause (with a pleasant or unpleasant sensation of its own) and the resulting love or hatred.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p02] And since pride and love are closely connected (as Hume observes, we seek to win others' love by showcasing the qualities we take pride in), the arguments of Part 1 can simply be carried over.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] In a series of eight "experiments", Hume tests his account against observations drawn from ordinary life.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] The final four experiments focus on how easily a transition is made from one passion to another.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] As Hume's account would predict, we easily go from love and hatred to pride and humility: e.g., I can take pride in my relation to someone else with lovable qualities.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Curiously, however, the reverse does not hold: e.g., my pride in my own qualities will not lead me to love someone else for their relation to me.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] To explain this, Hume argues that the imagination has trouble going from lively ideas to obscure ideas (e.g., from the idea of oneself to that of another person).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Next, as Hume's account would also predict, we easily transition from love of one person to love of others related to this person.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] But the transition is easiest when we "descend" from the greater to the lesser: e.g., "'tis more natural for us to love the son upon account of the father, than the father upon account of the son".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] And yet the imagination has the opposite tendency: e.g., moving easily from Jupiter's moons to Jupiter itself.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] To resolve this difficulty, Hume argues that it is easier for the passions to make minor changes (adding in the love of a related *lesser* person) than major changes (adding in the love of a related *greater* person), and that the passions "are a more powerful principle than the imagination".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Finally, Hume acknowledges a case where we can move easily from pride to love: "when the very cause of the pride and humility is plac'd in some other person", e.g. when your praise of me excites my pride and I end up loving you for it.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] But this exception only confirms Hume's account: since the first passion arises from the other person, we easily move to a passion directed at that same person.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume then confronts an objection: his account ignores intention, having us love or hate those who bring us pleasure or pain even where this is completely unintended.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] In response, Hume insists that qualities unrelated to intentional action really can elicit love or hatred, so long as the qualities are "constant and inherent in [someone's] person and character": e.g., disliking someone for their ugliness or stupidity.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] It is with isolated actions that intention is important: it "connect[s the action] with the person" and can also amplify the pleasantness or unpleasantness of the action, whereas "entirely involuntary and accidental" actions arouse only mild or short-lived passions.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] In a further illustration, Hume considers our emotional reaction to those who harm us from perfectly justified motives (e.g., judges, competitors): though we will not hate them if we are reasonable, we often hate them anyway, even inventing reasons to hate them.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] In the next two sections, Hume uses sympathy to account for some particular causes of love and hatred.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] First, "*relation*, *acquaintance*, and *resemblance*": we sometimes love others not for their personal qualities, but simply because they are related to us, familiar to us, or similar to us.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] In these cases, pleasure arises from the sheer stimulating effects of sympathy: family members, neighbors, and acquaintances are a durable source of lively ideas, as are individuals with personal qualities resembling our own.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] And as Hume puts it, "[e]very lively idea is agreeable, but especially that of a passion".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Second, we sometimes esteem people not for their personal qualities, but simply for being rich and powerful (esteem and contempt being "species of love and hatred").
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] To account for this phenomenon, Hume identifies three candidate "principles": (1) We enjoy thinking of their luxuries.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] (2) We think they might give us some of their wealth.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] He then argues that the third principle, sympathy, is by far the most important.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] The first principle has some influence on its own, but mostly operates by means of sympathy.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] And the second principle has little influence: it is relatively rare to receive any personal advantage from the rich and powerful, and we esteem them even when this is known to be impossible.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume closes the section with an overview of "the force of sympathy".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Many animals, and especially humans, have a psychological need for social interaction.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Moreover, sympathy with usefulness explains "[m]ost kinds of beauty": e.g., the convenience of a house, the fertility of a field.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Lastly, Hume observes that "the minds of men are mirrors to one another": a rich man enjoys his luxuries, which brings esteem from others, which in turn excites the rich man's pride, which encourages further pursuit of riches.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] The next six sections are dedicated to an examination of the "compound passions", i.e. passions arising from "the mixture of love and hatred with other emotions".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume begins with *benevolence* and *anger*, motivational "desires" aimed at bringing about "the happiness or misery of the person belov'd or hated".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] This marks an important contrast: love and hatred have innate motivational consequences, whereas pride and humility are only "pure emotions in the soul".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Like benevolence and anger, they are motivational desires aimed at bringing about another's happiness or misery; but unlike benevolence and anger, they apply quite generally—not only to those we love or hate, but even to complete strangers.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Thus Hume calls them "counterfeited" versions of benevolence and anger.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Pity (also called "compassion") is received by sympathetic communication: anyone can arouse our pity, just by communicating "their interests, their passions, their pains and pleasures" to us.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Even people who show no emotion at their misfortune can arouse our pity due to the influence of general rules on our imagination.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume also uses comparison to account for *envy*: the unpleasant feeling we experience when another's "present enjoyment" makes our own happiness seem diminished by comparison.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] The following section sees Hume amending his account in response to a problem.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] If love and hatred are produced by anyone who brings us pleasure or pain, as Hume has argued, then we should love those who bring us malicious joy, and hate those who bring us the pain of pity.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] But this runs contrary to experience: we tend to hate the objects of our malice, and love the objects of our pity.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume resolves this problem by introducing a new kind of relation of impressions: in addition to "the resemblance of sensations", there is also "the parallel direction of the desires".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Thus the connection between pity and love, and between malice and hatred, lies in their motivational tendencies (which run parallel to each other), not in the way they feel (which run contrary to each other).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume gives examples to illustrate and confirm this "principle of a parallel direction", including a discussion of the emotions found in business rivals and business partners.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] But another problem arises: since Hume says we have esteem for the rich and contempt for the poor, how can he say we tend to love the objects of our pity?
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume's solution presents us with three levels of sympathy with misfortune: (1) weak sympathy, which makes us feel only the present misfortune of the afflicted, producing only contemptuous pity; (2) strong sympathy (i.e.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] And because we have "a much stronger propensity to pride than to humility", there is more pride in contempt than there is humility in respect.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume then acknowledges a problem: why, given his account, are love and hatred not *always* accompanied by respect and contempt?
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume finishes with an explanation of why social inferiors are expected to keep their distance from their superiors.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] The final compound passion is "the amorous passion", i.e. romantic love.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] It consists of three distinct passions: a sense of beauty, libido, and kindness.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] These three passions are bound together both by "resemblance" (all have a pleasant sensation) and by "a parallel desire" (all have related motivational tendencies).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Accordingly, any one of them can end up producing the other two, with beauty most likely to produce the other two (kindness and libido being "too remote" from each other, and beauty "plac'd in a just medium betwixt them").
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume argues that this phenomenon reinforces his "double relation of impressions and ideas" account.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume finishes Part 2 with his last section on animal psychology.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Love and hatred, he writes, can be produced in animals simply by the pain or pleasure felt from an object, or by such relations as "acquaintance" and "likeness" of species.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Sympathy works to spread feelings (e.g. fear, grief) from one animal to another, keep animal play from leading to injury, and animate a pack of hunting dogs beyond their individual level of excitement.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] In general, Hume remarks, the psychological mechanisms at work do not require any sophisticated "force of reflection or penetration": "[e]very thing is conducted by springs and principles, which are not peculiar to man, or any one species of animals".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] In Part 3, Hume begins examining the motives that bring us to action.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] After a glancing mention of the direct passions and a perfunctory definition of the will as a mere impression we feel, he confronts the hoary philosophical problem of free will and determinism, dedicating two sections to a defense of soft determinist compatibilism.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] In the first section, he makes a case for "the doctrine of necessity".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] The issue, as Hume sees it, is whether human action is determined by a necessity comparable to "*physical necessity*"—the necessity that governs physical objects.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Thus, given Hume's idiosyncratic account of necessity, it is hard to deny that human action is governed by necessity.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] In the next section, Hume challenges "the doctrine of liberty"—the view that human beings are endowed with a distinctive kind of indeterministic free will—by setting out and debunking "the reasons for [its] prevalence".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] First, since we confuse necessity with violent constraint, we end up confusing freedom from necessity (the indeterministic "liberty of *indifference*") with freedom from violent constraint (the compatibilist "liberty of *spontaneity*").
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Second, we are deceived by a "false sensation of liberty": when deliberating about our own actions, there is "a certain looseness" to the will, so that we can easily produce an "image or faint motion" for each alternative course of action.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Thus, we end up convinced that we really could have acted differently, even though "a spectator can commonly infer our actions from our motives and character".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Finally, we mistakenly think necessity poses a threat to moral responsibility, and is therefore "dangerous... to religion and morality".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] After noting that being *dangerous* is not the same as being *false*, Hume recalls that his "necessity" is a very attenuated one: there is nothing dangerous or even controversial about saying that constant conjunction and causal inference apply to human action as well as physical objects.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Thus, the threat to moral responsibility comes not from *necessity*, but from *indeterministic liberty*.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume then passes from the will itself to the motivational factors that determine voluntary actions.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Against the traditional view that reason and the passions frequently come into motivational conflict, Hume argues that reason is incapable of opposing the passions, and that the passions cannot run contrary to reason.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] First, reason alone cannot motivate us—it can only perform demonstrative or causal reasoning.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] And since abstract demonstrations influence us only by directing causal reasoning (e.g., doing math to pay your debts), and causal reasoning influences us only by directing preexisting motives (e.g., figuring out how to make the food you want), reason itself cannot bring about any motivation.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] And this in turn means it cannot counteract or regulate the passions: on the contrary, "[r]eason is, and ought only to be the slave of the passions".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Second, passions cannot be in agreement or disagreement with reason: for this is a matter of the agreement or disagreement between an idea and the object it represents, and passions do not represent anything else.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Thus Hume notoriously writes: "'Tis not contrary to reason to prefer the destruction of the whole world to the scratching of my finger".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Of course, if a passion is based on a false judgement—about an object that does not really exist, or a causal relation that does not really hold—then the passion can be considered "unreasonable" in a less strict sense of the term.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] But "even then", insists Hume, "'tis not the passion, properly speaking, which is unreasonable, but the judgment".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Finally, Hume argues that the alleged conflict between reason and the passions is actually a conflict between two different kinds of passions—the calm passions and the violent passions.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Since both the calm passions and reason "operat[e] with the same calmness and tranquility", we confuse them with each other and mistakenly suppose our calm passions to be "determinations of reason".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] The following five sections examine the factors which give passions their motivational force.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Unsurprisingly, the violence of a passion makes it stronger; but even a calm passion can be extremely strong due to "repeated custom and its own force", especially when it has been "corroborated by reflection, and seconded by resolution".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Nevertheless, since "[g]enerally speaking, the violent passions have a more powerful influence on the will", Hume focuses on the factors which increase the violence of passions.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] First, when a "predominant passion" is accompanied by other "inferior" passions, it can acquire violence by "swallow[ing them] up": e.g., strong love can be made more violently passionate by a touch of anger.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Other psychological phenomena (e.g., opposition, uncertainty, obscurity) can produce the same effect by stimulating us with agitation and mental effort.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Next, "custom and repetition" can both leave us with a direct inclination to perform the activity we are repeating and also affect the violence of related passions.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume discusses three stages of repeated activity: (1) The sheer novelty of unfamiliar activities makes our feelings more intense, either magnifying our pain or adding on the pleasure of "wonder [and] surprise".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] (2) An activity performed with "moderate facility" is "an infallible source of pleasure" (cf.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] "flow"), sometimes even converting pain into enjoyment.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] (3) But excessive repetition can make formerly pleasant activities so dull as to be unpleasant.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Our passions can also acquire violence from *the vivacity of our ideas*.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Thus particular ideas make for more violent passions than general ideas, and so too for fresh memories, conventional ideas, and ideas enlivened by great eloquence or passionate delivery.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] And, as in Book 1, only beliefs (as opposed to "mere[s] fiction of the imagination") can call up any of our passions.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume also devotes two sections to examining the vivacity of our ideas of *space and time* and the corresponding effect on our passions.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] (2) Distance in time is associated with a greater reduction than distance in space, because our sensory experience makes it easier to hold an array of spatial points in mind than an array of temporal points.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] (3) The distant past is associated with a greater reduction than the distant future, because it is easier for the mind to go with the flow of time than to go against it.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] (2) Distance in time has a greater effect than distance in space (e.g., ancient relics are more admired than furniture from abroad), because we are challenged and invigorated by the greater difficulty of mentally traversing distance in time.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] (3) The distant past has a greater effect than the distant future (e.g., we admire our ancestors more than our posterity), because we are challenged and invigorated by the greater difficulty of going against the flow of time.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume finishes with a convenient summary of the preceding six sections.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] At last Hume examines *the direct passions*, dividing them into two classes.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] First and most prominently, there are those direct passions which arise immediately from pleasure or pain (in Hume's terminology, "good or evil")—this is simply due to "an *original* instinct" that orients us towards pleasure and away from pain.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] *Joy* and *grief*/*sorrow* arise from pleasure or pain that is "certain or probable".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] *Hope* and *fear* arise from pleasure or pain that is "uncertain" to some degree.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] *Desire*and*aversion* arise from pleasure and pain "consider'd simply".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] And *the will* "exerts itself" when pleasure or the absence of pain is within our power to obtain.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Second, there are those direct passions which "arise from a natural impulse or instinct, which is perfectly unaccountable": here Hume mentions benevolence, anger, hunger, and lust (in section 3 he had mentioned self-preservation and the love of one's children).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] These diverse instinct-based passions, Hume writes, "produce good and evil [i.e., pleasure and pain]", as opposed to the other direct passions, which arise from pleasure and pain.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume spends the rest of the section on *hope and fear*, starting with a simple account based on probability.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] In conditions of uncertainty, as the imagination fluctuates between a pleasant scenario and an unpleasant scenario, the passions follow suit, fluctuating between joy and grief.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] And since different passions can blend together (like the lingering notes of a string instrument), the mixture of joy and grief will end up producing either hope or fear.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Even utterly irrelevant circumstances, or something expected to be *pleasant*, can call up fear if shrouded in uncertainty.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume closes the section by begging off any discussion of subtle "variations" of hope and fear, or of the role of the will and the direct passions in animals.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Book 2 finishes with a brief section on *curiosity*—"the love of truth", which leads us to take pleasure in intellectual pursuits and achievements.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] For both the abstract truths of "mathematics and algebra" and the real-world truths of "morals, politics, natural philosophy", we do not care much about truth "merely as such".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Instead, there are three other factors chiefly responsible for "the pleasure of study": (1) Intellectual challenge: the exercise must force us to "fix our attention and exert our genius".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] (2) Importance/utility: the topic must be useful or important enough to "fix our attention" via "a remote sympathy" with those our work might help (a sympathy that even motivates scholars lacking in "public spirit").
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] (3) Direct concern: just as hunters and gamblers begin to care about success itself more than the reward it brings, likewise scholars begin to develop a direct concern for the scholarly problems they work on (this due to the aforementioned principle of a "parallel direction").
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Finally, Hume offers an account of the *social curiosity* that fuels gossip: since doubt and uncertainty are painful, especially when they concern events whose ideas are forceful, we are naturally curious about the happenings of our immediate social environment.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume begins Book 3 by examining the nature of moral evaluation, offering a critique of moral rationalism and a defense of moral sentimentalism: in the terms of his overall system, Hume is arguing that the evaluations in our mind are *impressions*, not *ideas*.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] His main target is the rationalism of such philosophers as Clarke and Balguy, which posits "eternal fitnesses and unfitnesses of things, which are the same to every rational being that considers them", in effect classifying morality alongside mathematics under "relations of ideas".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume's principal arguments against this rationalism rest on Book 2's thesis that there is no opposition between reason and the passions: reason alone cannot motivate us, and "passions, volitions, and actions" cannot be in agreement or disagreement with reason.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Nor can the morality of an action be founded on the true or false judgements causally linked to it: no immoral action is wrong due to its arising from a mistake of fact, or (contra Wollaston) due to its causing false judgements in others.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] After summing up this critique, Hume develops a "more particular" case against rationalism, recalling his system's two kinds of reasoning: "the comparing of ideas" and "the inferring of matter of fact".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Consider the immorality of parricide and incest: this cannot consist merely in the abstract relations at play, for the very same relations can be found in perfectly non-moral contexts involving inanimate objects and animals.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] This first section ends with the famous is-ought paragraph.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Hume is thus left endorsing a moral sentimentalism somewhat like that of Hutcheson: "Morality... is more properly felt than judg'd of".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] The moral evaluations in our mind are impressions—"nothing but *particular* pains or pleasures"—and Hume's task is to explain how certain kinds of "action, or sentiment, or character" produce these special moral sentiments in us.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] But a problem arises: since pleasant or painful feelings can be produced by inanimate objects, why does sentimentalism not succumb to the same objection Hume has just raised against rationalism?
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Second, he reminds us that the four indirect passions are produced by pleasant or unpleasant qualities in *ourselves or other persons*, not inanimate objects.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] This objection dispatched, Hume closes with two points about the psychological origin of moral sentiments.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] First, on the working assumption that nature tends to produce variety from "a few principles", he hopes to find "general principles" underlying our moral psychology.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p03] Before proceeding to his detailed examination of moral psychology, Hume takes a parting shot at moral rationalism and its "incomprehensible relations and qualities, which never did exist in nature, nor even in our imagination, by any clear and distinct conception".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume devotes Part 2 to the "artificial virtues": those positive character traits that would have no moral appeal were it not for social conventions established by human artifice.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] The most important of these virtues is *justice*, and in the first section Hume offers his so-called "circle argument" to show that justice would not be seen as a virtue in a hypothetical world lacking the relevant social conventions.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] First, Hume contends, *character-based motives* are morally more fundamental than *actions*: we approve of an action only insofar as it indicates some virtuous motive in the agent's character, so that what makes an action virtuous in the first place is the virtuous motive it proceeds from.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] But this motive must be an ordinary motive in human nature, as opposed to the distinctive moral motive of *performing the action because it is virtuous* (i.e., a "sense of duty").
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] After all, this moral motive presupposes that the action already counts as virtuous, and it would be circular to derive the action's virtue from a motive which itself presupposes the action's virtue.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And so if justice were a natural virtue, there would have to be an ordinary motive in human nature that could make someone obey the rules of justice.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Thus there is no motive capable of making justice count as a virtue, not until certain social conventions come into place.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume closes this section by adding that we evaluate motives largely by comparison with what we consider to be normal human psychology, and that the rules of justice are so "obvious" and "necessary" an invention that they can still be deemed "natural" to the human species.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume next devotes an important and lengthy section to two questions: First, how is the social convention of justice established?
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And second, why do we invest the rules of justice with moral significance?
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] His answer to the first question begins with our need for society.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Humans are not strong, skilled, or secure enough to meet our needs alone, and only society can offer additional labour force, specialisation, and mutual aid—all important advantages of society learned of through growing up in families.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] But this necessary social union is threatened both by human selfishness (or rather "confin'd generosity") and by the scarcity and instability of external goods.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] He insists that this convention is not a *promise*, famously illustrating the point with the example of two men agreeing to row a boat together, simply from a sense of mutual advantage rather than from any promise.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And as justice is defined in terms of such a convention, so too the related concepts of "*property*, or *right*, or *obligation*" can mean nothing in its absence.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Since the chief obstacle to society (our selfishness, especially our insatiable acquisitiveness) is in fact the very motive responsible for society, the growth of social order depends less on our moral qualities than on our intellectual qualities.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] But since stabilizing external goods is such a "simple and obvious" rule, the convention is established with little delay, so that "the *state of nature*" is a "mere philosophical fiction"—not very realistic but useful for theorizing.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Real-world cases also illustrate the idea: close personal relationships bring one's private belongings into common ownership, and free goods like air and water are allowed unrestricted use.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And this general point, Hume says, reinforces three earlier points: (1) Public benevolence cannot be why we obey the rules of justice, for it would only make these rules pointless.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] (2) Moral rationalism cannot make sense of justice: mere abstract reasoning can neither account for the fact that justice hinges on specific background conditions, nor produce the concern for our interests that originally leads us to establish the rules of justice.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] (3) Justice is an artificial virtue: though the whole purpose of justice is to serve our interests, the connection between justice and our interests dissolves in the absence of the relevant social convention.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] For without this convention, wholehearted pursuit of the *public interest* would make justice pointless and unrestrained pursuit of *private interests* would leave justice in ruins.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume's answer to the second question is that our approval of justice and disapproval of injustice is based in *sympathy with the public interest*.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Justice was established to serve our interests, but when society grows large enough, we might lose sight of how injustice threatens social order.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Fortunately, the threat can be made vivid again when I myself am the victim of injustice, or when I impartially sympathise with others threatened by injustice.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Their sympathetically communicated negative feelings form the basis of my disapproval of injustice, and this evaluation subsequently extends to my own behavior through the influence of general rules and sympathy with the opinions of others.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Three additional factors then reinforce these moral sentiments: (1) Public leaders propagandise on behalf of justice (contra Mandeville, this technique works only by appealing to and intensifying moral sentiments we already have).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] (2) Parents instill children with a reliable and deeply rooted concern for the rules of justice.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] (3) Concern for reputation makes us scrupulously avoid injustice as a matter of personal principle.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] The next four sections see Hume completing his examination of justice as an artificial virtue: he argues that "the three fundamental laws of nature, *that of the stability of possession*, *of its transference by consent*, and *of the performance of promises*" are all based on human convention.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] He begins by discussing the general rule of *stability* and its applications.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] To make a peaceful establishment of society, we must avoid controversial "particular judgements" about who is best suited to make use of what resources, and instead adopt a general rule of *present possession*, simply as a "natural expedient" with all the appeal of custom.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Once society has been established, the additional rules of *occupation* (i.e.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] "first possession"), *prescription* (i.e.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] "the fruits of our garden"), and *succession* (i.e. inheritance) are developed.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] These rules are largely the product of the imagination, with ownership determined by the association of ideas.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Second, because "rigid stability" would of course bring great disadvantages (resources having been allocated by mere "chance"), we need a peaceful way to induce changes in ownership: thus we adopt the "obvious" rule of *transference by consent*.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume then examines the final "law of nature"—*the performance of promises*—giving a two-stage argument that promise-keeping is an artificial virtue.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] First, promises are naturally unintelligible, for there is no distinctive mental act for promises to express, neither *resolutions* nor *desires* nor a direct *willing* of the act.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And as for *willing an obligation*, this is too absurd to be plausible: given that changes in obligation require changes in human sentiment, it is plainly impossible to will an obligation into existence.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] But second, even if promises *were* naturally intelligible, they could not create an obligation: i.e., even if we were foolish enough to mentally will an obligation, nothing would change, since no voluntary act could ever change human sentiments.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume also reprises the circle argument, arguing that there is no motive for promise-keeping other than a sense of duty in doing so.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] How, then, does the artificial convention of promising come about?
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] The first two laws of nature, for all their usefulness, leave many further opportunities for mutual advantage unrealised (e.g., non-simultaneous cooperative exchanges of labour), unable to overcome the meanness of human nature in the absence of "mutual confidence and security".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] The convention is then made moral in the same way as before ("*[p]ublic interest*, *education*, and *the artifices of politicians*") and a fictional act of the mind ("*willing* an obligation") is fabricated to make sense of the moral obligation.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Finally, Hume reviews these "laws of nature" and offers three additional arguments for their artificiality.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] (1) Justice is commonly defined in terms of property, and yet it is impossible to understand property except in terms of justice.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] But since there is no natural sentiment of approval for the practice of justice described in neutral language, "abstracting from the notio[n] of *property*" (e.g., restoring an object to its first possessor), justice is not a natural virtue.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] (2) Justice and injustice come in bright lines and sharp boundaries, whereas our natural moral sentiments come in degrees.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] In the next six sections, Hume completes his "system concerning the laws of nature and nations" with a lengthy discussion of *government*.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume then critiques the liberal Whig theory of government as deriving its authority only from the consent of the governed, as traced back to an original contract between ruler and people.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] But though government typically originates in a social agreement, promising cannot be its one and only source of authority.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] For, as Hume has argued, promise-keeping itself originates in a social convention serving the public interest, so that if government serves the public interest by "preserv[ing] order and concord in society", then it gains an authority of its own equivalent to that of promise-keeping.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And the two run parallel *morally* as well: promise-breaking and anti-government action are both disapproved of primarily from a sense of common interest.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Thus there is no sense founding the one in the other.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] But Hume agrees with the Whigs about the right of resistance when governments become tyrannical.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Our *interest* in government consists in "the security and protection, which we enjoy in political society", and therefore disappears as soon as the authorities become intolerably oppressive.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And though our *moral* obligation to allegiance might be expected to linger on stubbornly due to the influence of general rules, our familiarity with human nature and the history of tyrants will give us additional general rules marking out exceptions to the common rule.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And thus public opinion ("perfectly infallible" in questions of morality) is not wed to any exceptionless rule of "passive obedience", but is perfectly willing to "make allowances for resistance in the more flagrant instances of tyranny and oppression".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] The next problem of allegiance is *who exactly is the rightful ruler?* And according to Hume, such questions are often irresolvable by reason, and it can be wise to simply go with the flow in the "interests of peace and liberty".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Again, Hume agrees that political society begins with a social agreement promising allegiance to certain people.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] But once a government acquires its own authority by serving the public interest, it is (paradoxically) in our interest to renounce our interest and simply abide the powers that be, lest we fall into divisive controversies over the best possible ruler.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And with so many distinct principles, the choice of ruler is sometimes wonderfully clear, and sometimes hopelessly unclear.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume then examines international law: the similarities between individuals and entire nations yield the same three laws of nature as before, but the special needs of nations call for special rules (e.g., diplomatic immunity).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Only general practice can determine exactly how much weaker the obligation is, and indeed the fact that the rules are recognised to be weaker in practice shows that people have "an implicit notion" of their artificiality.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] The final section examines the social rules governing the sexual behavior of women ("chastity and modesty"), which Hume takes to nicely illustrate how artificial virtues grounded only in social interest can nevertheless acquire universal force.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] It is boringly obvious that these rules are not exactly natural, and yet they solve a natural problem: a child needs both parents, parents need to know the child is theirs, and paternity is subject to uncertainty.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And since questions of sexual fidelity cannot be settled in courtrooms, society needs informal norms (with weakened evidential standards and heightened reputational import) policing fidelity in women.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Indeed, Hume adds, given female weakness in the face of sexual temptation, society needs women to feel a strong aversion to anything even suggestive of infidelity.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Men instead stake their reputation on courage (a partly natural virtue) and enjoy looser sexual norms, fidelity in males (like cooperation among nations) being less important for society.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume finishes the *Treatise* by examining the "natural virtues": those character traits approved of independently of social conventions.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] In a general review of morality and the passions, he reminds us that human psychology is driven by pain and pleasure, which call up direct passions and then the indirect passions that explain moral evaluation and which "qualities or characters" count as virtuous or not.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And since the indirect passions apply to actions only as indicating something stable in the agent's mind, the moral sentiments are also directed primarily at "mental qualities" and only derivatively at actions.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] After this review, Hume presents his central "hypothesis" concerning the natural virtues and vices: moral evaluation of these traits is best explained in terms of sympathy.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Given these three points, and given that natural virtues and social utility often go together, parsimony dictates that we also explain the natural virtues in terms of sympathy.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume finds the connection between virtue and utility fairly obvious: it inspired Mandeville's erroneous account of virtue as a fraudulent invention of conniving politicians, and indeed the connection is even stronger with natural virtues than with artificial virtues.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] For though artificial virtues may harm society in particular cases (promoting the public interest only when mediated by a "general scheme"), natural virtues help society in every case, which makes it even more probable that sympathy explains moral evaluation of the natural virtues.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume further develops his sympathy-based account of the natural virtues by considering two objections.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] First, *variability and impartiality*: how can something as variable as sympathy account for moral impartiality of the sort that recognises virtue in loved ones and complete strangers alike?
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Indeed, we perform similar corrections for our senses and our aesthetic judgements.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Of course, our passions may resist correction, so that only our language is changed; but we still know that our emotional favoritism of some over others would go away if we were equally close to them all, which is perhaps enough to settle "a general calm determination of the passions".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Second, *moral luck*: how can sympathy explain cases where unusual external circumstances have prevented someone's internal character from having its usual effects?
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume's answer is that the imagination follows general rules, focusing more on something's general tendencies than its actual effects, and that our moral sentiments are influenced accordingly.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Naturally, we will feel even stronger approval when the general tendency is actually realised, but we deliberately set aside moral luck to correct our general moral judgements.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] This explains how we can manage such "extensive sympathy" in morality despite our "limited generosity" in practice: it takes "*real consequences*" and particular cases to "touch the heart" and "controul our passions", but "*seeming tendencies*" and general trends are enough to "influence our taste".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] He finishes this general treatment of the natural virtues with a fourfold classification: every natural virtue is either (1) useful to others, (2) useful to the person himself, (3) immediately agreeable to others, or (4) immediately agreeable to the person himself.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] The two categories of useful virtues are often blended together by sympathy: what hurts me ends up paining others as they sympathise with me, and what hurts others ends up paining me as I sympathise with them.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Less important are the virtues of immediate agreeableness: instead of reflecting on the positive tendencies of a mental quality, we simply find it pleasant in and of itself (e.g. wit, insouciance).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And even here sympathy plays a major role: we approve of these virtues in large part because they bring pleasure to others or the person himself.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume then applies his "general system of morals" to two kinds of virtue: the rough "heroic virtue" of the *great*, and the kind-hearted virtue of the *good*.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] As for heroic virtue, it derives its merit from a suspect source: pride.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Pride has a bad name because the idea of someone superior to us can be so immediately disagreeable, but Hume distinguishes between "ill-grounded" and "well-grounded" pride.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Ill-grounded pride pains us by *comparison*, when someone else overrates their own merit and this idea of a superior becomes more than an "idle" fiction and reaches a medium level of strength.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] But someone else's well-grounded pride brings us pleasure by *sympathy*, when the idea is so strong in us that we fully believe in their merit.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] And thus well-grounded pride is a virtue, thanks to its usefulness and agreeableness to the person himself.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Now, because we are so prone to the vice of excessive pride, social harmony demands artificial rules ("*rules of good-breeding*") against the open expression of any pride at all.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] But "a man of honour" is still expected to have a healthy internal sense of his own merit, and those whose modesty goes too far are scorned for their "meanness" or "simplicity".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Thus it is that heroic virtues—"[c]ourage, intrepidity, ambition, love of glory, magnanimity, and all the other shining virtues of that kind"—are chiefly admired for the "well-regulated pride" they embody.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume adds that our disapproval of open pride even in those who have never insulted us (e.g. historical figures) is due to an additional sympathy with the people around them.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] As for the virtues of "goodness and benevolence", Hume explains their merit primarily in terms of their positive impact on others.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] The section begins by reviewing Hume's account of moral evaluation from the common point of view, and of sympathy with a person's sphere of influence.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Here the "tender passions" are not only themselves good for society, they are needed to direct other virtues towards the public good.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] But there is also a more immediate approval, as we are simply "touch'd with a tender sentiment" or sympathetic to characters like our own—this is why even benevolent "trifles" and excesses in love still win approval, as the love in their minds easily converts into love in our minds for them.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Indeed, in general, your moral virtue is mostly determined by how desirable you are in different social relations.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume finishes by explaining how his system accommodates not only the "moral virtues" but also the "natural abilities" of the mind, and by downplaying the distinction as not very important and largely a matter of mere terminology.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Virtues and abilities are alike, Hume contends, in their "causes and effects": they are mental qualities that produce pleasure and elicit approval, and we all care about both.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] To the objection that the distinction matters because the approval of abilities feels different from the approval of virtues, Hume responds that our approval of different things always feels different (e.g., with different virtues).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] These natural abilities of the mind are valued mainly for their usefulness for the person himself: e.g. prudence, sagacity, industry, patience.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Sometimes immediate agreeableness is most important, whether to others (e.g. wit, eloquence, charisma, even cleanliness) or the person himself (e.g. cheerfulness).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Our judgements are influenced by empirical associations between a quality and a person's age or walk of life (e.g., disapproval of levity in the old).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Natural abilities also influence our evaluations by making an able person more consequential in life, for good or ill.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Thus far Hume's account has dealt exclusively with mental qualities, but he goes some way to accommodate "bodily advantages" and "the advantages of *fortune*", which are equally capable of eliciting "love and approbation".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Thus women love a strong man in sympathy with the utility a lover of his could be expected to receive, everyone finds beauty in healthy and useful body parts, and an immediate pleasure or dismay arises from the perception of regular features or "a sickly air", respectively.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Thus we esteem the wealthy by sympathy with the pleasure their riches give them, reinforced by their being more consequential.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume notes that, though he cannot explain why, the feeling of approval is more determined by the kind of subject contemplated (e.g., an inanimate object, or a person) than by the kind of mechanism driving the approval (e.g., sympathy with utility, or immediate agreeableness).
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] The conclusion of Book 3, and therefore the *Treatise* as a whole, briefly recapitulates the reasoning for Hume's thesis that "sympathy is the chief source of moral distinctions".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Indeed, most would agree that justice and "the useful qualities of the mind" are valued for their usefulness, and what besides sympathy can explain why we care about the public good or "the happiness of strangers"?
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] This "system of ethics" is not only supported by "solid argument", Hume adds, but it can help moralists show the "*dignity*" and the "*happiness*" of virtue.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] First, it puts morality in a good light to see it derived from "so noble a source" as sympathy: we end up approving of virtue, the sense of virtue, and even the psychological principles underlying the sense of virtue.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Secondly, a life of virtue pays off quite well, bringing immediate advantages, an enhanced social reputation, and the "inward satisfaction" of a mind able to "bear its own survey".
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] So, while Hume presents himself as a theoretical "anatomist" who dissects human psychology into ugly bits, his work is well-suited for the practical "painter" who styles morality into a beautiful and inviting ideal.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] The *Treatise* has appeared in many editions since the death of the author.
[src:alice-crary/a-treatise-of-human-nature-p04] Hume's *Treatise* inspired Albert Einstein, who in a 1915 letter explained "The theory of relativity suggests itself in positivism.
[src:alice-crary/alice-crary] Alice Marguerite Crary was born in 1967 in Seattle, Washington.
[src:alice-crary/alice-crary] During high school, she was a national champion rower at the Lakeside School (Seattle) in Seattle, Washington, and competed internationally and placed 6th in the Junior Women's Eight at the 1985 World Rowing Junior Championships in Brandenburg, Germany.
[src:alice-crary/alice-crary] Later in the 1980s, after studying liberation theology with Harvey Cox at Harvard Divinity School, Crary researched Christian base communities in southern Mexico and Guatemala.
[src:alice-crary/alice-crary] In the early 1990s, she was a teacher at the Colegio Americano in Quito, Ecuador.
[src:alice-crary/alice-crary] Crary earned her PhD in philosophy from the University of Pittsburgh in 1999.
[src:alice-crary/alice-crary] Crary is a university distinguished professor at the Graduate Faculty of The New School for Social Research in New York City and visiting fellow at Regent’s Park College, University of Oxford (where she was professor of philosophy 2018–19).
[src:alice-crary/alice-crary] She held visiting fellowships at All Souls College, Oxford (2021–22), and the Institute for Advanced Study, School of Social Sciences (2017–18).
[src:alice-crary/alice-crary] Crary frequently participates in and organizes events for public discussion, such as public debates on the valuation of life and the treatment of animals and the cognitively disabled.
[src:alice-crary/alice-crary] She has also written for the *New York Times*.
[src:alice-crary/alice-crary] Crary's first monograph, *Beyond Moral Judgment*, discusses how literature and feminism help to reframe moral presuppositions.
[src:alice-crary/alice-crary] Her *Inside Ethics* argues that ethics in disability studies and animal studies is stunted by a lack of moral imagination, caused by a narrow understanding of rationality and by a philosophy severed from literature and art.
[src:alice-crary/alice-crary] Crary has promoted the view that humans and animals have moral worth above and beyond any quantitative valuation.
[src:alice-crary/alice-crary] Crary's work on feminism is critical of standard views of objectivity in analytic philosophy and post-structuralism.
[src:alice-crary/alice-crary] Drawing on Wittgenstein and feminist theory, Crary rejects the view that objectivity is value-neutral, and thus incompatible with ethical and political perspectives.
[src:alice-crary/alice-crary] According to Crary, these "ethically-loaded perspectives" invite both cognitive and ethical appreciation for the lives of women, in ways that count as objective knowledge.
[src:alice-crary/alice-crary] Crary is associated with the so-called "therapeutic" or "resolute" reading of Wittgenstein.
[src:alice-crary/alice-crary] She co-edited a collection of essays of such readings, *The New Wittgenstein*, where her own contribution argues against the standard use-theory readings of Wittgenstein that often render his thought as politically conservative and implausible.
[src:alice-crary/alice-crary] She has contributed to collections of Wittgenstein scholarship, including interpretations of Wittgenstein's *On Certainty*.
